      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. My concern is that by framing it that way, I might inadvertently teach the students that originalism is just a way to stop progress, rather than a legitimate legal philosophy. If I present the 'intent' of the 14th Amendment as a way to justify these rights, am I not just side-stepping the legal argument that the word 'substantive' doesn't actually appear in the text? It feels like the argument for substantive due process is more about achieving a specific social outcome than it is about strict legal interpretation. How can I teach this while remaining completely neutral on whether the doctrine is a legitimate legal tool or just judicial activism?",
